shared_text:
North Cedar Jr/Sr High School
June 4 at 4:01 PM ¬∑

Based on the latest guidance from Governor Reynolds, we have made the following decisions regarding April/May events that had been postponed until June.

Regarding Prom - due to the continued limits on group size and social distancing requirements, we have made the difficult decision to cancel Prom. We had high hopes that by postponing until late June we would be able to host this event. Unfortunately, the concerns about COVID-19 have continued longer than originally expected. I know this is a big disappointment to students, but I hope everyone can understand this decision was made in the best interest of everyone's health and safety.

Regarding Graduation - we will hold the ceremony on June 28 @ 2:00 p.m. in the school gymnasium. We will be following all the safety guidelines including 50% capacity, limits on family group size, and 6 feet social distancing between groups. Detailed plans and expectations will be shared with seniors and their parents next week.

shared_text:
North Cedar Boys Basketball
June 1 at 9:01 PM ¬∑

Unfortunately due to our current pandemic situation a lot of our summer basketball plans have been severely clipped. The North Cedar Youth Basketball Camp has been cancelled but we look forward to getting it up and going next year!

We still have a few high school opportunities to be had in the gym starting in July and I will be getting more info out as soon as I can.

Last summer‚Äôs integration with larger schools and tougher competition made us better but now have been put in charge of our own improvements. Get shots up at home or at the park, work your ball handling, rewatch film from last year and ask yourself where you could get better! Take advantage now because the season will be here quicker than you think!

post_text:
Several members of the 36 member NC FBLA ( Future Business Leaders of America) chapter competed virtually this week at Iowa‚Äôs first virtual State Leadership Conference. Congratulations to the chapter and the following members. Those that earned 4th place or better are automatically asked to compete at the virtual NLE (National Leadership Experience) held the June 29-July 1.

Our chapter placed 4th place for increase in local chapter membership - 15 members.
Our chapter placed 3rd in largest percentage of increase in local chapter membership - 71.43%.
Kayla Syring - 6th in Business Communications
Breylee and Olivia - 3rd in Community Service Project
Karly Cerda - 5th Computer Problem Solving
Matt - 1st Computer Problem Solving
Fiona - 4th Job Interviewing
Toby - 1st Computer Applications

All freshmen through seniors are eligible to join FBLA. If interested contact a Mrs. Koch for more information at jkoch@north-cedarstu.org.

post_text: Congratulations to Carson Cornelius! During the fall Intro to Business class. as well as Personal Finance. students were given the opportunity to invest $100,000 (fake) in current stocks and bonds using the Stock Market Game online provided by SIFMA Foundation. Students learn to buy and sell stocks and bonds online just as if they had their own eTrade like account. Just recently the game ended and Carson was in 1st Place (1 out of 188 in our Region (MI, IA, IN or OR)) earnings percentage return of 68.48%; total equity $168, 479.14. Not bad for approx. 6 month investments. Super job and congratulations Carson!

7th through 12th grade students may come to the Jr/Sr High School to pick up locker, locker room & music items on these dates and times:

Wednesday, April 22nd, from 9am to 1pm or 5pm to 7pm
Thursday April 23rd, from 9am to 1 pm or 5pm to 7pm
Friday, April 24th, from 9am to 1pm

Students will be met at the entrance by the main office by staff and brought their bag of locker contents. Take this time to bring in any library books to school when you pick up your items. Please remember to practice 6 foot social distancing as you wait for your items to be brought to you.

Elementary will send out a message about picking up items later this week.

North Cedar will be joining ‚ÄúLight Up Iowa‚Äù by lighting up our stadium at 8:00pm each Friday night. We want to show our students how much we miss them. At 8:00pm Friday nights, we will turn on the lights of our stadium and leave them on for one minute for each day we have been out of school. We invite our families to drive by and see the lights. To maintain social distancing, please stay in your vehicle. We ask that you do not walk on the track.

Number of minutes through end of April:
April 10 15 minutes
April 17 20 minutes
April 24 25 minutes

#lightupIA

Event/Activity Changes due to COVID-19

North Cedar Jr/Sr High School
April 6 at 2:03 PM ¬∑

With the extension of school closure through April 30, we have made decisions on the following events/activities:

Spring Play - cancelled

Prom - rescheduled for June 20

Graduation - still scheduled for May 17. Will reschedule for late June, if necessary.

Driver's Ed - classroom component via Zoom starting April 7th. Driving component will resume when COVID-19 closure is over.

Each decision was made after careful consideration by the school staff directly involved with each event/activity. We are doing our best to keep as many events on the calendar as possible and will update you as the weeks go by and additional decisions are made.

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1-I1BjD4zpCP9Ia7SIZNA5MglEa_z1G73eHXwMqoMvOc/edit?usp=sharing

If you have questions about events not listed in this document, please email Principal Bendixen at mbendixen@north-cedarstu.org or Adam Hadenfeldt at ahadenfeldt@north-cedarstu.org

post_text:
As North Cedar is closed in response to COVID-19, we are committed to continuing to support your students' learning. North Cedar offers a number of ways for students to engage in learning even while they are away from school.

The teachers and principals will be meeting next Monday and Tuesday to finalize a document that will house all the resources we will be sharing with you. We anticipate to have this sent out to parents by Thursday of next week.

The activities shared with you will not take the place of regular classroom instruction, but will supplement student learning at home. These activities are meant to provide optional opportunities for student learning while they are absent from school. We encourage families to continue student learning at home.

We appreciate your partnership as we navigate this unknown territory together. Please feel free to reach out through email if you have any questions or concerns along the way.

Take Care,
Principal Bendixen
Principal Horman

North Cedar School Nutrition Department will be starting meal service on Wednesday, March 18th from 11am-11:30am. Pick up will be at each of the four school buildings:

Lowden at Lowden Elementary
Clarence at Clarence Jr/ Sr High
Stanwood at Stanwood District Offices
Mechanicsville at Mechanicsville Elementary

Staff will be outside each entrance meeting individuals who need meals. Please make sure to stay at least 6 feet away from individuals when picking up. We will be providing services on Monday, Wednesday and Fridays until further notice. Individuals can pick up two breakfast and two lunch meals per student on Monday and Wednesday. On Friday there will be one lunch and one breakfast per student.

If you haven't signed for meals, you can do so at anytime by calling the building offices or emailing Jen Smith - jsmith@north-cedarstu.org

Thank you.

North Cedar CSD Nutritional Department

March 6 at 3:26 PM ¬∑ Mechanicsville, IA ¬∑

On Friday, Mechanicsville Elementary had Knight Pride groups. Each student created their own leprechaun trap snack with graham crackers, pretzels, big marshmallows, and a scoop of lucky charms to use as bait. They enjoyed eating their trap as they listened to the book "How to Catch a Leprechaun." After the story, each Knight Pride Group used miscellaneous materials to create a life-size leprechaun trap. They did a great job of working together and strategizing on what would work best to catch a leprechaun.

North Cedar Community School District added 12 new photos.
March 6 at 3:42 PM ¬∑

On Monday, March 2, Mechanicsville Elementary kicked off Read Across America by celebrating Dr. Seuss's birthday and inviting community members to share how they use reading in their jobs. Each classroom then had a community guest read a special book to them. A special thank you to all our community readers: Lee Crock (farmer), Sarah Subbert (naturalist), Lonni & Jake Koch (ambulance & fire department), Tracy Schroeder (Bubba's Restaurant), Jane Pini (Mechanicsville Library & singer), Drew Montz (Coralville Police Officer), Cheryl Coppess (Bridge Community Bank), Adam Hadenfeldt (North Cedar Coach), Dylan Montz (sports journalist), Jackie Kennon (KCRG reporter) and Morgan Wilson (lawyer, Iowa Legal Aid)

Ms. Harr's 3rd grade students in Mechanicsville were each given an owl pellet to dissect. First, they described the characteristics of the outside of the owl pellet (size, shape, color, and texture). Then they opened the pellet up and carefully looked at the bones that were in it. Finally, they compared the animal bones from their pellet to that of a human bone. Finding a "skull" in their pellet was a big deal!

February 3 at 2:34 PM ¬∑

Mechanicsville Knight Pride Groups met on Friday, January 31st. They read the book "Snowflake Bently" and discussed how we are all unique and special just like snowflakes. Next, each student made their own "melted snowman" snack out of pudding (body), chocolate chips (eyes and mouth), and Mike & Ike's (for a nose). Then they ended their Knight Pride Time together by each of them cutting out snowflakes, that will be displayed in our halls.

post_text: Intro to Business is doing a leadership program called Lead4Change where you find a local issue that you would like to help out with. One of the project members stated that they have family members that are elementary staff (not from NC) and talk about how much they spend of their own money on classroom supplies. After researching online and finding out that nearly every public school teacher spends on the average $480 a year on their classroom (reported by National Center of Education Statistics), the Lead4Change group decided to make NC Elementary their project. After surveying elementary staff, pricing out items they needed, the group figured out they need approx. $600 to stuff their stockings with these needed supplies. Please help them make this a project a reality for our North Cedar Elementary Staff.

post_text:
Hello Sophomores and Juniors-
The Workplace Learning Connection Internship portal is now open for summer internship opportunities. An internship is an opportunity for you to earn hands on experience in a career field of your choice (with even the possibility of the business of your choice!). Several students who have participated in internships have also had the opportunity to be employed within the company they interned at. Internships are a 45 hour commitment and some businesses will work with you on creating a flexible schedule. After completing the 45 hour internship, you will earn 1 high school credit.

Applications can be found at: http://www.kirkwood.edu/site/index.php?p=38531

Applications are due on February 7th before noon.

9th-11th Graders Parents:

If you have a student interested in taking any Kirkwood class next year either at the high school, online, or at Jones Regional Center, NOW is the time to apply to start their KW record and begin the process! Students are not committing to anything at this point. This is for new students only. Additional info will be coming soon on offerings and how to sign up along with their high school courses. Some courses will require placement testing before February so plan ahead. All Kirkwood courses are at no direct cost to students/families and are a great way to explore careers and get a jump start in college! www.kirkwood.edu/earncredit >> Apply to earn CCHS. After this is complete, be sure to activate your k number and password in the welcome letter! Call Craig or Lisa if you have any questions. 319-465-2302.
